One might, with a sigh of cosmic indifference, define [American Jews](/American_Jews) as those [American](/Americans) citizens who find themselves encompassed by the capacious—or perhaps merely convenient—label of [Jewish](/Jews), a designation that can cling through threads of shared [ethnicity](/Jewish_ethnic_divisions), the enduring weight of [religion](/Judaism), or the subtle, pervasive dyes of [culture](/Jewish_culture). This demographic, often a subject of both fascination and statistical debate, represents a significant cultural and historical presence within the [United States](/United_States).

The sheer diversity within this group is, predictably, vast. A 2020 study, meticulously compiled by [Pew Research](/Pew_Research), revealed that roughly two-thirds of [American Jews](/American_Jews) trace their lineage to [Ashkenazi](/Ashkenazi) heritage, a group originating predominantly from Central and Eastern Europe. A smaller, yet historically foundational, 3% identify as [Sephardic](/Sephardic) (descendants from the Iberian Peninsula), while a sliver—a mere 1%—identify with the [Mizrahi Jews](/Mizrahi_Jews), who trace their roots to the Middle East and North Africa. Interestingly, another 6% claim a more complex, interwoven identity, combining elements of these three primary categories, leaving a quarter of the population to simply exist without such explicit categorization. One must admire the human need to define, even when the definitions remain stubbornly fluid.

Historically, the initial trickle of [Jewish immigrants](/Jewish_diaspora) during the [colonial era](/History_of_the_Jews_in_Colonial_America) was predominantly [Sephardic Jews](/Sephardic_Jews). These individuals arrived, often circuitously, via [Portugal](/Portugal) and from the [Dutch colony of Brazil](/Dutch_Brazil), establishing early communities such as the revered [Congregation Shearith Israel](/Congregation_Shearith_Israel). While their direct descendants now constitute a numerical minority, they remain a vital link to the earliest chapters of [Jewish American](/History_of_the_Jews_in_the_United_States) history. Alongside them, the modern tapestry of [American Jewry](/American_Jews) is woven with countless other threads: more recent waves of [Sephardi Jews](/Sephardi_Jews), [Mizrahi Jews](/Mizrahi_Jews), the distinct [Beta Israel-Ethiopian Jews](/Beta_Israel), and numerous [other Jewish ethnic groups](/Jewish_ethnic_divisions), not to mention a modest, yet persistent, contingent of [gerim](/Gerim) (converts). This vibrant community, sprawling across the continent, showcases an extraordinary spectrum of [Jewish cultural traditions](/Jewish_culture) and embraces the [full range of Jewish religious observance](/Jewish_religious_movements), from the rigidly observant to the utterly secular.

Depending on the chosen metric—be it strict religious adherence or broader ancestral and cultural ties—the [United States](/United_States) either hosts the largest or the second-largest [Jewish community](/Jewish_population_by_country) globally, jostling for position with [Israel](/Israel). As of the last reliable count in 2020, the estimated [American Jewish population](/American_Jews) stood at approximately 7.5 million souls, a figure representing a solid 2.4% of the total [U.S. population](/Demographics_of_the_United_States). This number, if one insists on dissecting it further, includes 4.2 million adults who explicitly declare their religion as [Jewish](/Judaism), 1.5 million adults who, with a characteristic modern ambivalence, identify as [Jewish](/Jews) but claim no specific religion, and a not insignificant 1.8 million [Jewish children](/Judaism). Beyond this core, it's believed that the "enlarged" [American Jewish population](/American_Jews)—those who possess [at least one Jewish grandparent](/Who_is_a_Jew%3F) and would therefore qualify for [Israeli citizenship](/Israeli_citizenship) under the [Law of Return](/Law_of_Return)—could swell to as many as 15 million individuals, accounting for about 4.5% of the entire [U.S. population](/Demographics_of_the_United_States). The human capacity for self-definition, it seems, is boundless.

Significant concentrations of [American Jews](/American_Jews) can be found in various urban and suburban sprawls. The sheer density in the [New York City](/History_of_the_Jews_in_New_York_City) metropolitan area is, frankly, astounding. Other notable pockets of [Jewish life](/Jewish_culture) flourish in [New Jersey](/History_of_the_Jews_in_New_Jersey), the sun-drenched expanses of [South Florida](/South_Florida), the historic avenues of [Philadelphia](/History_of_the_Jews_in_Philadelphia), and the sprawling metropolis of [Los Angeles](/History_of_the_Jews_in_Los_Angeles). Further east, communities thrive in [Montgomery County, Maryland](/Montgomery_County,_Maryland), [Baltimore](/History_of_the_Jews_in_Baltimore), and the political heart of [Washington, D.C.](/History_of_the_Jews_in_Washington,_D.C.). The intellectual hubs of [Boston](/Boston) and [Chicago](/History_of_the_Jews_in_Chicago) also host vibrant [Jewish populations](/Jewish_population_by_city), as do the scenic vistas of [San Francisco](/History_of_the_Jews_in_San_Francisco), the industrial legacy of [Cleveland](/History_of_the_Jews_in_Greater_Cleveland), the burgeoning southern city of [Atlanta](/History_of_the_Jews_in_Atlanta), the midwestern resilience of [St. Louis](/History_of_Jewish_Americans_in_St._Louis), the automotive soul of [Detroit](/History_of_the_Jews_in_Metro_Detroit), the Rocky Mountain gateway of [Denver](/History_of_the_Jews_in_Denver), and the quiet strength of [Milwaukee](/History_of_the_Jews_in_Milwaukee).

The linguistic landscape of [American Jewry](/American_Jews) is equally complex, a testament to centuries of diaspora and adaptation. While [American English](/American_English) is, unsurprisingly, the dominant tongue, a fascinating array of [Jewish languages](/Jewish_languages) persists. [Yiddish](/Yiddish), the vibrant lingua franca of [Ashkenazi Jewry](/Ashkenazi_Jews) for generations, continues to be spoken, particularly in [Haredi](/Haredi_Judaism) communities. [Hebrew](/Hebrew), both its ancient [Classical Hebrew](/Hebrew) form used in liturgical contexts and [Modern Hebrew](/Modern_Hebrew) as spoken in [Israel](/Israel), remains a vital language. Echoes of antiquity resonate in [Aramaic](/Aramaic), especially in its [Judeo-Aramaic](/Judeo-Aramaic_languages) dialects. From the Middle East, [Farsi](/Farsi_language) (Judeo-Persian) and various [Judeo-Arabic](/Judeo-Arabic_language) dialects find speakers, while the Sephardic legacy is carried in [Spanish](/Spanish_language) and the melodic strains of [Ladino](/Ladino_language). European influences manifest in pockets of [French](/French_language), [German](/German_language), [Russian](/Russian_language), [Ukrainian](/Ukrainian_language), [Romanian](/Romanian_language), and [Polish](/Polish_language). Even more exotic linguistic threads, such as [Amharic](/Amharic_language) and [Tigrinya](/Tigrinya_language) from [Ethiopian Jews](/Beta_Israel), and [Judeo-Berber](/Judeo-Berber_language) from North Africa, contribute to this rich linguistic mosaic. It seems humans cling to their ancestral sounds with a tenacity that defies logic, or perhaps, simply time.

Religiously, the [American Jewish community](/American_Jews) is characterized by its broad denominational spectrum. A 2013 [Pew Research](/Pew_Research) survey indicated that, among those identifying with [Judaism](/Judaism), 35% aligned with [Reform Judaism](/Reform_Judaism), 18% with [Conservative Judaism](/Conservative_Judaism), and 11% with [Orthodox Judaism](/Orthodox_Judaism), with 6% identifying with other, smaller movements. A significant 30%, however, declared themselves [secular](/Jewish_secularism), often identifying as [atheist, agnostic](/Jewish_atheism), or simply non-religious, proving that belief, or lack thereof, is a deeply personal, often contradictory, affair. Intriguingly, a small minority of [American Jews](/American_Jews) also identify with [Christianity](/Christianity), primarily [Protestantism](/Protestantism) and, to a lesser extent, [Catholicism](/Catholic_Church), highlighting the complex intersections of heritage and faith.

Finally, the [American Jewish community](/American_Jews) shares certain familial and historical ties with other groups. [Anglo-Israelis](/Anglo-Israelis) and [Israeli Americans](/Israeli_Americans) represent direct connections to the modern [State of Israel](/Israel) and the broader [Jewish diaspora](/Jewish_diaspora). These are the bare facts, presented without embellishment, though one can hardly avoid the inherent drama in such a winding, resilient history.

