### History

Main article: [History of the Jews in the United States](/History_of_the_Jews_in_the_United_States)

Further information: [Antisemitism in the United States](/Antisemitism_in_the_United_States) and [History of antisemitism in the United States](/History_of_antisemitism_in_the_United_States)

The presence of [Jews](/Jews) in the nascent [Thirteen Colonies](/Thirteen_Colonies) dates back to the mid-17th century, a fact that often surprises those who assume American history began with a more homogenous population. However, their numbers were initially quite modest, barely reaching 200 to 300 individuals by the turn of the 18th century. These intrepid early arrivals were predominantly [Sephardi Jewish](/Sephardi_Jews) immigrants, primarily of Western Sephardic (also known as [Spanish and Portuguese Jewish](/Spanish_and_Portuguese_Jews)) lineage, bringing with them a rich heritage from their [diaspora](/Jewish_diaspora) communities. Yet, by 1720, a demographic shift was already underway, with [Ashkenazi Jews](/Ashkenazi_Jews) from Central and Eastern European [diaspora](/Jewish_diaspora) communities beginning to outnumber their Sephardic predecessors, a pattern that would continue to define [American Jewry](/American_Jews) for centuries.

A pivotal legislative change, the English [Plantation Act of 1740](/Plantation_Act_1740), offered a crucial, albeit pragmatic, pathway for [Jews](/Jews) to attain [British citizenship](/British_citizenship) and, more importantly, to legally emigrate to [the colonies](/British_America). This was a significant step towards greater integration, though not without its lingering prejudices. The American narrative often highlights figures like [Chaim Salomon](/Chaim_Salomon), a Polish-born [Jew](/Jews) who arrived in [New York](/New_York_(state)) and, with a flair for finance, became an indispensable figure in the [American Revolution](/American_Revolution). His efforts in fundraising were, by all accounts, instrumental in securing the financial backing required for the patriotic cause, demonstrating early on the profound impact [Jewish individuals](/Jews) would have on the nation's destiny.

Despite facing persistent limitations, such as being denied the right to vote or hold public office in various local jurisdictions, [Sephardi Jews](/Sephardi_Jews) began to assert themselves in civic life during the 1790s. This period saw them finally granted political equality in the five states where their communities were most established, a hard-won victory in the slow march towards full integration. For a time, until around 1830, [Charleston, South Carolina](/History_of_the_Jews_in_Charleston,_South_Carolina), held the distinction of hosting the largest [Jewish population](/Jewish_population_by_city) in [North America](/North_America), a testament to its early openness and economic opportunities.

The 19th century witnessed the commencement of large-scale [Jewish immigration](/Immigration_to_the_United_States). By mid-century, a substantial wave of [German Jews](/History_of_the_Jews_in_Germany), fleeing increasingly restrictive and [antisemitic](/Antisemitism) laws in their homelands, arrived on American shores. These newcomers, often educated and entrepreneurial, quickly established themselves as merchants and shop-owners, laying the groundwork for many enduring family businesses. The eastward migration of early [Jewish arrivals](/Jews) gradually extended westward, leading to the remarkable event in the fall of 1819: the first recorded [Jewish religious services](/Jewish_prayer) west of the [Appalachian Range](/Appalachian_Mountains), held during the [High Holidays](/High_Holidays) in [Cincinnati](/Cincinnati). This city would, over time, become a crucible for innovation in [American Judaism](/American_Judaism), particularly under the visionary leadership of Rabbi [Isaac Meyer Wise](/Isaac_Meyer_Wise), widely regarded as the father of [Reform Judaism](/Reform_Judaism) in the [United States](/United_States). Wise championed progressive practices, notably the inclusion of women in the [minyan](/Minyan), a significant departure from traditional norms. The latter half of the 1800s saw further growth in the region with the influx of more [German](/German_Jews) and [Lithuanian Jews](/Lithuanian_Jews), contributing to the establishment of institutions like [Manischewitz](/Manischewitz), now one of the largest producers of [American kosher products](/American_Jewish_cuisine) (presently based in [New Jersey](/New_Jersey)), and *[The American Israelite](/The_American_Israelite)*. Founded in 1854 in [Cincinnati](/Cincinnati), this newspaper holds the distinction of being the oldest continuously published [Jewish newspaper](/Jewish_media) in the [United States](/United_States) and the second-oldest globally, a persistent voice in a changing world. By 1880, the [Jewish population](/Jewish_population_by_country) in the [United States](/United_States) had swelled to approximately 250,000. This community was largely composed of educated, often secular, [German Jews](/German_Jews), though a smaller, influential segment of older [Sephardi Jewish](/Sephardi_Jews) families continued to exert their presence.

The late 19th and early 20th centuries marked an epochal shift in [Jewish migration](/Jewish_diaspora) to the [United States](/United_States). Beginning in the early 1880s, the trickle became a torrent, fueled by escalating persecution and dire economic conditions across parts of [Eastern Europe](/Eastern_Europe). The vast majority of these new arrivals were [Yiddish](/Yiddish_language)-speaking [Ashkenazi Jews](/Ashkenazi_Jews), primarily hailing from the impoverished [diaspora](/Jewish_diaspora) communities of the [Russian Empire](/History_of_the_Jews_in_Russia) and the infamous [Pale of Settlement](/Pale_of_Settlement), regions that today encompass modern-day [Poland](/Poland), [Lithuania](/Lithuania), [Belarus](/Belarus), [Ukraine](/Ukraine), and [Moldova](/Moldova). During this same tumultuous period, significant numbers of [Ashkenazic Jews](/Ashkenazi_Jews) also emigrated from [Galicia](/Galicia_(Eastern_Europe)), then one of the most impoverished and densely [Jewish](/Jews) urbanized regions of the [Austro-Hungarian Empire](/Austria-Hungary), primarily driven by the relentless pressures of economic hardship. [Romania](/History_of_the_Jews_in_Romania) also contributed a substantial cohort of [Jewish emigrants](/Jews). Between the late 19th century and the restrictive [Immigration Act of 1924](/Immigration_Act_of_1924), over 2,000,000 [Jews](/Jews) landed on American shores. Most gravitated towards the [New York metropolitan area](/New_York_metropolitan_area), transforming it into one of the world's most significant concentrations of [Jewish population](/Jewish_population_by_city). The cultural impact was profound: by 1915, daily [Yiddish](/Yiddish) newspapers in [New York City](/New_York_City) alone boasted a circulation of half a million, with national circulation reaching 600,000, not to mention the countless weekly papers and magazines.

The dawn of the 20th century saw these newly arrived [Jews](/Jews) rapidly construct intricate support networks. These consisted of numerous small [synagogues](/Synagogue) and *[Landsmanshaften](/Landsmanshaft)* (German and [Yiddish](/Yiddish) for "Countryman Associations"), which provided crucial social and economic lifelines for immigrants from the same towns or villages, recreating a sense of community in an alien land. Simultaneously, influential [American Jewish writers](/Jewish_American_literature) of the era fervently advocated for [assimilation](/Jewish_assimilation) and seamless integration into the broader [American culture](/Culture_of_the_United_States). This push, combined with the inherent dynamism of the immigrants, led to [Jews](/Jews) quickly becoming an integral part of American life. A remarkable half a million [American Jews](/American_Jews) (representing roughly half of all [Jewish males](/Jews) between 18 and 50) served in [World War II](/World_War_II). The post-war era saw a new trend: younger [Jewish families](/Jews) joined the sweeping movement of [suburbanization](/Suburbanization). In these new suburban landscapes, [Jews](/Jews) became increasingly assimilated, a phenomenon accompanied by a noticeable rise in [intermarriage](/Interfaith_marriage). The suburbs inadvertently fostered the emergence of new communal centers, as [Jewish school](/Jewish_day_school) enrollment more than doubled between the end of [World War II](/World_War_II) and the mid-1950s. Similarly, [synagogue](/Synagogue) affiliation surged from a mere 20% in 1930 to 60% by 1960, with the most rapid expansion observed in [Reform](/Reform_Judaism) and, notably, [Conservative congregations](/Conservative_Judaism). More recent waves of [Jewish emigration](/Jewish_diaspora) from the former [Soviet Union](/History_of_the_Jews_in_the_Soviet_Union) and other regions have, by and large, integrated into this established, multifaceted [American Jewish community](/American_Jews).

Over the years, [Americans](/Americans) of [Jewish descent](/Jews) have achieved remarkable success across an astonishing array of fields and endeavors. The [Jewish community in America](/American_Jews) has, with tenacious resolve, ascended from being relegated to the [lower class](/American_lower_class) of society, often facing explicit barriers to employment, to a group characterized by high concentrations in academia and a per capita income that consistently surpasses the national average in the [United States](/United_States). It is a trajectory that speaks volumes about perseverance, ambition, and perhaps, a collective cosmic stubbornness.

