### Self-identity

Scholars, with their predictable penchant for intellectual debate, endlessly ponder whether the historical experience of [Jews](/Jews) in the [United States](/United_States) has been so singularly unique as to truly validate the concept of [American exceptionalism](/American_exceptionalism) for this group. Korelitz (1996) offers a compelling argument, illustrating how [American Jews](/American_Jews) during the late 19th and early 20th centuries deliberately shed a [racial definition](/Racial_identity) of [Jewishness](/Jewish_identity) in favor of one that embraced the more malleable concept of [ethnicity](/Ethnic_identity). The linchpin for understanding this significant transition, from a perceived racial self-definition to a more cultural or ethnic one, can be found within the pages of the *[Menorah Journal](/Menorah_Journal)* between 1915 and 1925. During this pivotal decade, contributors to the *Menorah* vigorously promoted a [cultural](/Culture) understanding of [Jewishness](/Jewish_identity), consciously moving away from racial, religious, or other rigid frameworks. This was a strategic maneuver to define [Jews](/Jews) in a world that, with its relentless pressures, threatened to dilute and absorb the very essence of [Jewish uniqueness](/Jewish_peoplehood). The journal, in essence, served as the ideological standard-bearer for the Menorah movement, a collective endeavor spearheaded by [Horace M. Kallen](/Horace_M._Kallen) and others, dedicated to fostering a revival of [Jewish cultural identity](/Jewish_culture) and actively dismantling the archaic notion of race as the primary determinant of peoples.

Siporin (1990) further illuminates this discussion, suggesting that the intricate web of family [folklore](/Folklore) among [ethnic Jews](/Ethnic_Jews) provides invaluable insights, transforming collective history into a form of living art. These narratives, he argues, offer a profound understanding of the enduring resilience of [Jews](/Jews) in the face of displacement and profound transformation. Many immigrant narratives, predictably, often bear the heavy theme of the arbitrary nature of fate and the diminished status of newcomers navigating an alien culture. In stark contrast, later ethnic family narratives tend to depict the individual as more in control of their own destiny, albeit sometimes at the perceived risk of entirely losing their [Jewishness](/Jewish_identity). Some particularly poignant stories showcase how a family member skillfully navigated the inherent tension between maintaining an [ethnic identity](/Ethnic_identity) and embracing an [American one](/American_culture). After 1960, the haunting memories of [the Holocaust](/The_Holocaust), coupled with the existential shock of the [Six-Day War](/Six-Day_War) in 1967, exerted profound and undeniable impacts on the ongoing fashioning of [Jewish ethnic identity](/Ethnic_identity). Some commentators have persuasively argued that [the Holocaust](/The_Holocaust) starkly underscored for [Jews](/Jews) the paramount importance of their [ethnic identity](/Ethnic_identity) at a historical juncture when other minority groups were vociferously asserting their own. The world's largest [Jewish gathering](/Jewish_gathering) outside of [Israel](/Israel) recently occurred in [Edison](/Edison,_New_Jersey), central [New Jersey](/New_Jersey), on December 1, 2024, a testament to the community's enduring vitality and collective spirit.

