In the bustling urban landscape of [New York City](/New_York_City), while the [German-Jewish community](/German_Jews) was comfortably entrenched 'uptown' in its established affluence, the more numerous [Jews](/Jews) who migrated from [Eastern Europe](/Eastern_Europe) found themselves in the 'downtown' crucible of tension, particularly with their [Irish](/Irish_Americans) and [German Catholic](/German_Americans) neighbors. This friction was exacerbated by the fact that [Irish Catholics](/Irish_Americans) held considerable sway over [Democratic Party](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) politics [at the time](/Tammany_Hall), leading to predictable clashes over resources and influence. Despite these challenges, [Jews](/Jews) carved out a formidable niche for themselves in the garment trades and within the powerful needle unions in [New York](/New_York_(state)). By the 1930s, their collective voice had become a significant political force in [New York](/New_York_(state)), offering staunch support for the most progressive initiatives of the [New Deal](/New_Deal). They remained a steadfast component of the [New Deal Coalition](/New_Deal_Coalition), extending particular and enthusiastic backing to the burgeoning [Civil Rights Movement](/Civil_Rights_Movement). However, by the mid-1960s, the emergence of the [Black Power movement](/Black_Power_movement) regrettably fostered a growing, though often reluctant, separation between [Blacks](/African_Americans) and [Jews](/Jews), even as both groups largely remained firmly within the [Democratic camp](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)).

Earlier [Jewish immigrants](/Jews) from [Germany](/Germany) tended, perhaps surprisingly, to lean politically [conservative](/Conservatism). Many, including the devoutly [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) [Louis Marshall](/Louis_Marshall), held the conviction that [Jews](/Jews) should ideally avoid any singular political alignment whatsoever, a sentiment that now seems quaint. Conversely, the massive influx of [Jews](/Jews) from [Eastern Europe](/Eastern_Europe), commencing in the early 1880s, generally brought with them a more [liberal](/Left-wing_politics) or [left-wing](/Left-wing_politics) political orientation, quickly establishing themselves as the new political majority within the [American Jewish community](/American_Jews). Many arrived in [America](/United_States) with direct experience in socialist, [anarchist](/Jewish_Anarchism), and communist movements, as well as the influential [Labor Bund](/General_Jewish_Labor_Union), all emanating from the intellectual ferment of [Eastern Europe](/Eastern_Europe). These experiences propelled many [Jews](/Jews) into leadership roles within the early 20th-century [American labor movement](/American_labor_movement), where they played a pivotal role in founding unions that, in turn, became major players in [left-wing politics](/Left-wing_politics) and, after 1936, in the evolving landscape of [Democratic Party](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) politics.

Historically, [American Jews](/American_Jews) generally gravitated towards the [Republican party](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) during the latter half of the 19th century and the early years of the 20th. This alignment was partly reinforced by the pronounced [Evangelical](/Evangelicalism) imagery frequently employed by [William Jennings Bryan](/William_Jennings_Bryan) and other [Populist Democrats](/Populism), which, perhaps inadvertently, ignited anxieties about [Antisemitism](/Antisemitism) among [American Jews](/American_Jews). Additionally, [Republican candidates](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) such as [William McKinley](/William_McKinley) and [Theodore Roosevelt](/Theodore_Roosevelt) enjoyed considerable popularity among [Jewish voters](/American_Jews_in_politics). However, the political compass of the majority of [Jews](/Jews) has consistently pointed towards the [Democratic Party](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) since at least 1916, when 55% cast their votes for [Woodrow Wilson](/Woodrow_Wilson), a trend that solidified dramatically by 1928, when a significant 72% supported the ultimately unsuccessful candidacy of [Al Smith](/Al_Smith).

With the election of [Franklin D. Roosevelt](/Franklin_D._Roosevelt), [American Jews](/American_Jews) became an even more solidly [Democratic voting bloc](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)). Their support for [Roosevelt](/Franklin_D._Roosevelt) reached a staggering 90% in both the 1940 and 1944 elections, a level of unwavering allegiance that has been matched only once since. In the 1948 election, [Jewish support](/American_Jews_in_politics) for [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) [Harry S. Truman](/Harry_S._Truman) saw a slight dip to 75%, with 15% diverting their votes to the newly formed [Progressive Party](/Progressive_Party_(United_States,_1948)). A testament to sustained lobbying efforts and a strategic desire to better compete for the [Jewish vote](/American_Jews_in_politics), both major party platforms had, since 1944, included a distinctly [pro-Zionist](/Zionism) plank, explicitly supporting the creation of a [Jewish state](/Israel). This, however, appeared to have little immediate effect on voting patterns, as a remarkable 90% continued to vote for parties other than [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)). In every subsequent election, with the notable exception of 1980, no [Democratic presidential candidate](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) has secured less than 67% of the [Jewish vote](/American_Jews_in_politics). (The 1980 election saw [Carter](/Jimmy_Carter) receive 45% of the [Jewish vote](/American_Jews_in_politics), a significant anomaly discussed further below.)

During the 1952 and 1956 elections, [Jewish voters](/American_Jews_in_politics) consistently cast 60% or more of their ballots for [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) [Adlai Stevenson](/Adlai_Stevenson_II). In a rare show of Republican strength, [General Eisenhower](/Dwight_Eisenhower) managed to garner 40% of the [Jewish vote](/American_Jews_in_politics) for his re-election bid, marking the best performance for the [Republicans](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) since [Warren G. Harding](/Warren_G._Harding)'s 43% in 1920. The 1960 election saw a solid 83% of [Jewish voters](/American_Jews_in_politics) opt for [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) [John F. Kennedy](/John_F._Kennedy) over [Richard Nixon](/Richard_Nixon). In 1964, an overwhelming 90% of [American Jews](/American_Jews) lent their support to [Lyndon Johnson](/Lyndon_Johnson), decisively rejecting his [arch-conservative Republican](/Conservatism) opponent, [Barry Goldwater](/Barry_Goldwater). [Hubert Humphrey](/Hubert_Humphrey) secured 81% of the [Jewish vote](/American_Jews_in_politics) in the 1968 elections, despite his ultimate loss to [Richard Nixon](/Richard_Nixon) in the presidential race.

The [Nixon](/Richard_Nixon) re-election campaign of 1972 found [Jewish voters](/American_Jews_in_politics) exhibiting a degree of apprehension regarding [George McGovern](/George_McGovern), resulting in only 65% favoring the [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)). This shift allowed [Nixon](/Richard_Nixon) to more than double [Republican Jewish support](/American_Jews_in_politics) to a notable 35%. In the 1976 election, [Jewish voters](/American_Jews_in_politics) demonstrated renewed allegiance to [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) [Jimmy Carter](/Jimmy_Carter), supporting him by 71% over incumbent [President Gerald Ford](/Gerald_Ford), who secured 27% of the [Jewish vote](/American_Jews_in_politics). However, the [Carter](/Jimmy_Carter) re-election campaign in 1980 saw a dramatic decline in [Jewish support](/American_Jews_in_politics) for the [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)), plummeting to just 45%. [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) victor [Ronald Reagan](/Ronald_Reagan) garnered 39% of the [Jewish vote](/American_Jews_in_politics), while a significant 14% went to independent candidate (and former [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States))) [John Anderson](/John_B._Anderson), illustrating a rare moment of splintered allegiance.

During the [Reagan](/Ronald_Reagan) re-election campaign of 1984, the [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) incumbent managed to retain 31% of the [Jewish vote](/American_Jews_in_politics), while 67% voted for [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) [Walter Mondale](/Walter_Mondale). The 1988 election saw [Jewish voters](/American_Jews_in_politics) favor [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) [Michael Dukakis](/Michael_Dukakis) by 64%, with [George H. W. Bush](/George_H._W._Bush) polling a respectable 35%. However, during [Bush's](/George_H._W._Bush) re-election attempt in 1992, his [Jewish support](/American_Jews_in_politics) dramatically dropped to a mere 11%, with 80% voting for [Bill Clinton](/Bill_Clinton) and 9% opting for independent candidate [Ross Perot](/Ross_Perot). [Clinton's](/Bill_Clinton) re-election campaign in 1996 maintained robust [Jewish support](/American_Jews_in_politics) at 78%, with 16% supporting [Bob Dole](/Bob_Dole) and 3% for [Perot](/Ross_Perot).

The [2000 presidential election](/2000_United_States_presidential_election) marked a historical first: [Joe Lieberman](/Joe_Lieberman) became the first [American Jew](/American_Jews) to run for national office on a major-party ticket, chosen as [Democratic presidential candidate](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) [Al Gore](/Al_Gore)'s vice-presidential nominee. The elections of 2000 and 2004 saw sustained [Jewish support](/American_Jews_in_politics) for [Democrats Al Gore](/Al_Gore) and [John Kerry](/John_Kerry) (a Catholic, for those keeping score), remaining firmly in the high- to mid-70% range. Meanwhile, [Republican George W. Bush](/George_W._Bush)'s re-election in 2004 witnessed a slight, but noticeable, increase in [Jewish support](/American_Jews_in_politics), rising from 19% to 24%.

In the landmark [2008 presidential election](/2008_United_States_presidential_election), a commanding 78% of [Jews](/Jews) cast their votes for [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama), who, with historical significance, became the first [African American](/African_Americans) to be elected president. This robust support for [Obama](/Barack_Obama) was particularly pronounced among white [Jews](/Jews), 83% of whom voted for him, a figure significantly higher than the 34% of white [Protestants](/Protestantism) and 47% of white [Catholics](/Catholic_Church) who did the same. Even among those identifying with other religions (67%) and those claiming no religion (71%), [Obama](/Barack_Obama) found strong backing.

The February [2016 New Hampshire Democratic Primary](/Democratic_Party_presidential_primaries,_2016) saw [Bernie Sanders](/Bernie_Sanders) achieve a notable milestone, becoming the first [Jewish candidate](/Jews) to win a state's presidential primary election. For congressional and senate races, [American Jews](/American_Jews) have consistently voted 70–80% for [Democrats](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) since 1968. This support further intensified for [Democratic House candidates](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) during the 2006 elections, reaching an impressive 87%.

[David Levy Yulee](/David_Levy_Yulee) holds the distinction of being the first [American Jew](/American_Jews) to serve in the [Senate](/United_States_Senate), representing [Florida](/Florida) from 1845–1851 and again from 1855–1861. At the commencement of the [112th Congress](/112th_United_States_Congress), 19 [Jews](/Jews) were among the 435 [U.S. Representatives](/United_States_House_of_Representatives). This group included 26 [Democrats](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) and one lone [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)), [Eric Cantor](/Eric_Cantor). While many of these members represented coastal cities and suburbs with substantial [Jewish populations](/Jewish_population_by_city), others hailed from regions not typically associated with large [Jewish communities](/Jews), such as [Kim Schrier](/Kim_Schrier) of [Seattle, Washington](/Washington_(state)); [John Yarmuth](/John_Yarmuth) of [Louisville, Kentucky](/Kentucky); and [David Kustoff](/David_Kustoff) and [Steve Cohen](/Steve_Cohen_(politician)) of [Memphis, Tennessee](/Tennessee). The total number of [Jews](/Jews) serving in the [House of Representatives](/United_States_House_of_Representatives) saw a decline from 31 in the [111th Congress](/111th_United_States_Congress). [John Adler](/John_Adler) of [New Jersey](/New_Jersey), [Steve Kagan](/Steve_Kagan) of [Wisconsin](/Wisconsin), [Alan Grayson](/Alan_Grayson) of [Florida](/Florida), and [Ron Klein](/Ron_Klein) of [Florida](/Florida) all lost their re-election bids. [Rahm Emanuel](/Rahm_Emanuel) resigned to assume the role of the President's Chief of Staff, and [Paul Hodes](/Paul_Hodes) of [New Hampshire](/New_Hampshire) chose not to seek re-election, instead making an unsuccessful bid for his state's open [Senate seat](/United_States_Senate). [David Cicilline](/David_Cicilline) of [Rhode Island](/Rhode_Island) was the sole [Jewish American](/American_Jews) newly elected to the [112th Congress](/112th_United_States_Congress), having previously served as the Mayor of [Providence](/Providence,_Rhode_Island). The number further diminished with the resignations of [Jane Harman](/Jane_Harman), [Anthony Weiner](/Anthony_Weiner), and [Gabby Giffords](/Gabby_Giffords) during the [112th Congress](/112th_United_States_Congress).

As of January 2014, a small but notable contingent of five openly [gay men](/LGBT) served in [Congress](/United_States_Congress), two of whom were [Jewish](/Jews): [Jared Polis](/Jared_Polis) of [Colorado](/Colorado) and [David Cicilline](/David_Cicilline) of [Rhode Island](/Rhode_Island). In November 2008, [Cantor](/Eric_Cantor) was elected as the [House Minority Whip](/Party_whips_of_the_United_States_House_of_Representatives), marking the first time a [Jewish Republican](/Jews) had been chosen for such a prominent leadership position. By 2011, he ascended to become the first [Jewish House Majority Leader](/House_Majority_Leader). He held this significant role until 2014, when he resigned shortly after his unexpected loss in the [Republican primary election](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) for his [House seat](/United_States_House_of_Representatives).

A 2013 [Pew Research](/Pew_Research) study revealed that a substantial 70% of [American Jews](/American_Jews) identified with or leaned towards the [Democratic Party](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)), while a mere 22% aligned with or leaned towards the [Republican Party](/Republican_Party_(United_States)). The [114th Congress](/114th_United_States_Congress) included 10 [Jews](/Jews) among its 100 [U.S. Senators](/United_States_Senate): nine [Democrats](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) ([Michael Bennet](/Michael_Bennet), [Richard Blumenthal](/Richard_Blumenthal), [Brian Schatz](/Brian_Schatz), [Benjamin Cardin](/Benjamin_Cardin), [Dianne Feinstein](/Dianne_Feinstein), [Jon Ossoff](/Jon_Ossoff), [Jacky Rosen](/Jacky_Rosen), [Charles Schumer](/Charles_Schumer), [Ron Wyden](/Ron_Wyden)), and [Bernie Sanders](/Bernie_Sanders), who, after a brief foray as a [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) to [run for President](/Bernie_Sanders_2016_presidential_campaign), returned to the [Senate](/United_States_Senate) as an [Independent](/Independent_politician). In the more recent [118th Congress](/118th_United_States_Congress), the number of [Jewish U.S. Representatives](/United_States_House_of_Representatives) stands at 28, with 25 being [Democrats](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) and 3 [Republicans](/Republican_Party_(United_States)). All 10 [Jewish Senators](/United_States_Senate) in this [Congress](/United_States_Congress) are [Democrats](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)).

Furthermore, a notable six members of [President Joe Biden](/Joe_Biden)'s cabinet were [Jewish](/Jews), a significant representation within the highest echelons of government. This distinguished group included [Secretary of State](/United_States_Secretary_of_State) [Antony Blinken](/Antony_Blinken), [Attorney General](/United_States_Attorney_General) [Merrick Garland](/Merrick_Garland), [Director of National Intelligence](/Director_of_National_Intelligence) [Avril Haines](/Avril_Haines), [White House Chief of Staff](/White_House_Chief_of_Staff) [Ron Klain](/Ron_Klain), [Homeland Security Secretary](/United_States_Secretary_of_Homeland_Security) [Alejandro Mayorkas](/Alejandro_Mayorkas), and [Treasury Secretary](/United_States_Secretary_of_the_Treasury) [Janet Yellen](/Janet_Yellen).

### Participation in civil rights movements

See also: [Jews in the civil rights movement](/Jews_in_the_civil_rights_movement)

Members of the [American Jewish community](/American_Jews) have consistently been among the most prominent and active participants in various [civil rights](/Civil_rights) movements throughout the nation's history, a fact often overlooked but critical to understanding their societal role. In the mid-20th century, [American Jews](/American_Jews) were notably at the forefront of both the [Civil Rights Movement](/Civil_Rights_Movement) for racial equality and the burgeoning [feminist](/Feminist) movements, advocating for broader social justice. Furthermore, a significant number of [American Jews](/American_Jews) have been influential figures in the ongoing struggle for [gay rights in America](/LGBT_rights_in_the_United_States).

The profound connection between [Jewish history](/Jewish_history) and the pursuit of freedom was eloquently articulated by [Joachim Prinz](/Joachim_Prinz), then president of the [American Jewish Congress](/American_Jewish_Congress), when he addressed the historic [March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom](/March_on_Washington_for_Jobs_and_Freedom) from the podium of the [Lincoln Memorial](/Lincoln_Memorial) on August 28, 1963. His words, delivered with a gravitas born of centuries of [persecution](/Persecution_of_Jews), resonate still: "As [Jews](/Jews) we bring to this great demonstration, in which thousands of us proudly participate, a twofold experience—one of the spirit and one of our history.&#160;... From our [Jewish historic experience](/Jewish_history) of three and a half thousand years we say: Our ancient history began with [slavery](/Slavery) and the yearning for freedom. During the [Middle Ages](/Middle_Ages) my people lived for a thousand years in the [ghettos of Europe](/Ghetto).&#160;... It is for these reasons that it is not merely sympathy and compassion for the [black people of America](/African_Americans) that motivates us. It is, above all and beyond all such sympathies and emotions, a sense of complete identification and solidarity born of our own painful historic experience." This statement serves as a potent reminder of the deep-seated empathy and shared struggle that fueled [Jewish participation](/Jews_in_the_civil_rights_movement) in these crucial movements.

### The Holocaust

During the tumultuous period of [World War II](/World_War_II), the [American Jewish community](/American_Jews) found itself tragically and deeply fractured, a disunity that, in retrospect, rendered it largely incapable of forming a cohesive and effective united front against the unfolding horrors. The majority of [Jews](/Jews) who had previously emigrated to the [United States](/United_States) from [Eastern Europe](/Eastern_Europe) were fervent supporters of [Zionism](/Zionism), convinced that a return to their ancestral homeland was the singular, viable solution to the relentless [persecution](/Persecution_of_Jews) and systematic [genocide](/The_Holocaust) then ravaging [Europe](/Europe). A significant, if somber, development during the latter stages of the war was the sudden, collective conversion of many previously ambivalent [American Jewish leaders](/Jewish_leadership) to the [Zionist cause](/Zionism), a shift undoubtedly catalyzed by the escalating reports of atrocities. What is particularly damning, and a truth that still stings, is that [the Holocaust](/The_Holocaust) was, for the most part, shockingly ignored by [American media](/Media_of_the_United_States) as it was actually happening. Reporters and editors, perhaps out of a profound inability to comprehend such barbarity, largely dismissed or downplayed the harrowing stories of atrocities emanating from a distant [Europe](/Europe).

[The Holocaust](/The_Holocaust), once its full, unspeakable scope became undeniable, left an indelible and profound impact on the [Jewish community](/American_Jews) in the [United States](/United_States). This impact intensified significantly after 1960, as [Holocaust education](/Holocaust_education) gradually improved, allowing [Jews](/Jews) to begin the agonizing process of comprehending what had transpired. The community grappled, and continues to grapple, with how to commemorate this cataclysm and how to integrate its lessons into their collective future. [Abraham Joshua Heschel](/Abraham_Joshua_Heschel) encapsulated this profound dilemma with chilling precision when he attempted to articulate the incomprehensible reality of [Auschwitz](/Auschwitz_concentration_camp): "To try to answer is to commit a supreme blasphemy. [Israel](/Israel) enables us to bear the agony of [Auschwitz](/Auschwitz_concentration_camp) without radical despair, to sense a ray [of] God's radiance in the jungles of history." These are truths that cling like glitter.

### International affairs

[Zionism](/Zionism) transformed into a well-organized and influential movement within the [U.S.](/United_States), largely due to the impassioned involvement of leaders such as [Louis Brandeis](/Louis_Brandeis) and the potent promise embedded in the [Balfour Declaration](/Balfour_Declaration) of a reconstituted [Jewish homeland](/Land_of_Israel). During the 1930s, [Jewish Americans](/American_Jews) actively organized and participated in large-scale boycotts of [German merchandise](/Germany) to protest the increasingly aggressive policies of [Nazi Germany](/Nazi_Germany). [Franklin D. Roosevelt](/Franklin_D._Roosevelt)'s [leftist domestic policies](/New_Deal) garnered robust [Jewish support](/American_Jews_in_politics) throughout the 1930s and 1940s, as did his staunchly anti-Nazi foreign policy and his advocacy for the nascent [United Nations](/United_Nations). While growing in influence, overt support for political [Zionism](/Zionism) during this period remained a distinct minority opinion among [Jews](/Jews) in the [United States](/United_States) until roughly 1944–45. This shift was tragically precipitated by the undeniable public revelation of the systematic mass murder of [Jews](/Jews) in [Nazi-occupied countries](/Nazi-occupied_countries), a horror confirmed with the liberation of the [Nazi concentration camps](/Nazi_concentration_camps) and [extermination camps](/Extermination_camp). The subsequent founding of the modern [State of Israel](/Israel) in 1948 and its swift recognition by the [American government](/United_States_government) (despite initial objections from American isolationists) served as a powerful testament to both intrinsic support and a desperate, global response to the unfathomable horrors of [the Holocaust](/The_Holocaust).

This burgeoning attention was rooted in a natural affinity and profound support for [Israel](/Israel) within the [Jewish community](/American_Jews). It was also, inevitably, fueled by the ensuing and perpetually unresolved conflicts surrounding [Israel's](/Israel) founding and the evolving role of the [Zionist movement](/Zionism). A vigorous internal debate erupted following the [Six-Day War](/Six-Day_War). The [American Jewish community](/American_Jews) found itself deeply divided over the Israeli response, though the vast majority ultimately accepted the war as a regrettable necessity. Similar tensions were ignited by the 1977 election of [Menachem Begin](/Menachem_Begin) and the rise of [Revisionist](/Revisionist_Zionism) policies, the devastating [1982 Lebanon War](/1982_Lebanon_War), and the enduring administrative governance of portions of the [West Bank](/West_Bank) territory. Disagreement over [Israel's](/Israel) 1993 acceptance of the [Oslo Accords](/Oslo_Accords) further fractured [American Jews](/American_Jews), mirroring a similar schism within [Israel](/Israel) itself, and ultimately leading to a parallel rift within the powerful [pro-Israel lobby](/Israel_lobby_in_the_United_States), with some even criticizing the [United States](/United_States) for its "blind" support of [Israel](/Israel). Discarding any pretense of unity, both segments began to establish separate advocacy and lobbying organizations. The liberal proponents of the [Oslo Accord](/Oslo_Accord) channeled their efforts through groups like [Americans for Peace Now](/Americans_for_Peace_Now) (APN) and the [Israel Policy Forum](/Israel_Policy_Forum) (IPF), organizations generally sympathetic to the [Labour government](/Israeli_Labor_Party) in [Israel](/Israel). They diligently sought to assure [Congress](/United_States_Congress) that [American Jewry](/American_Jews) stood firmly behind the [Accord](/Oslo_Accord) and defended the administration's efforts to support the fledgling [Palestinian Authority](/Palestinian_Authority) (PA), including pledges of financial aid. In a battle for public opinion, the IPF even commissioned numerous polls to demonstrate widespread communal support for [Oslo](/Oslo_Accord).

In direct opposition to [Oslo](/Oslo_Accord), a formidable alliance of conservative groups, including the [Zionist Organization of America](/Zionist_Organization_of_America) (ZOA), Americans For a Safe Israel (AFSI), and the [Jewish Institute for National Security Affairs](/Jewish_Institute_for_National_Security_Affairs) (JINSA), worked tirelessly to counteract the influence of the liberal [Jewish factions](/Jews). On October 10, 1993, the opponents of the Palestinian-Israeli accord converged at the American Leadership Conference for a Safe Israel, issuing stark warnings that [Israel](/Israel) was, in their view, prostrating itself before "an armed thug," and ominously predicting that "the thirteenth of September is a date that will live in infamy." Some [Zionists](/Zionism) also leveled harsh criticisms against [Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin](/Yitzhak_Rabin) and [Shimon Peres](/Shimon_Peres), his foreign minister and the chief architect of the peace accord. With the [community](/American_Jews) so profoundly divided, [AIPAC](/American_Israel_Public_Affairs_Committee) and the Presidents Conference, ostensibly tasked with representing a unified national [Jewish consensus](/Jews), struggled mightily to maintain a semblance of civil discourse amidst the increasingly antagonistic rhetoric. Reflecting these deep-seated tensions, [Abraham Foxman](/Abraham_Foxman) of the [Anti-Defamation League](/Anti-Defamation_League) was compelled by the conference to apologize for criticizing [ZOA's Morton Klein](/Morton_Klein). The conference, which, by its own organizational guidelines, was responsible for moderating communal discourse, reluctantly censured some [Orthodox](/Orthodox_Judaism) spokespeople for attacking [Colette Avital](/Colette_Avital), the Labor-appointed [Israeli Consul General](/Consul_General) in [New York](/New_York_(state)) and an ardent supporter of that particular vision of a peace process. Such are the inevitable fractures when deeply held convictions collide.

### Demographics

Further information: [Jews in New York City](/Jews_in_New_York_City)

#### Jewish Americans by state according to the American Jewish Yearbook, 2020 and the US Census Bureau

As of 2020, the [American Jewish population](/American_Jews) holds a rather peculiar distinction: depending on the chosen [method of identification](/Jewish_population_by_country)—whether one adheres to strict [halakhic](/Halakha) considerations or opts for more secular, [political](/Law_of_Return), and [ancestral identification](/Who_is_a_Jew%3F) factors—it is either the largest [Jewish community](/Jewish_population_by_country) in the world or the second-largest, just behind [Israel](/Israel). Precise population figures, much like precise definitions of anything meaningful, tend to vary. In 2001, for instance, there were approximately four million declared adherents of [Judaism](/Judaism) in the [U.S.](/United_States), constituting about 1.4% of the total [U.S. population](/Demographics_of_the_United_States). More recently, the [Jewish Agency](/Jewish_Agency) reported for 2023 that [Israel](/Israel) was home to 7.2 million [Jews](/Jews) (a commanding 46% of the world's [Jewish population](/Jewish_population_by_country)), while the [United States](/United_States) contained 6.3 million (40.1%).

According to collaborative findings from [Gallup](/Gallup,_Inc.) and the [Pew Research Center](/Pew_Research_Center), "at maximum 2.2% of the [US adult population](/Demographics_of_the_United_States) has some basis for [Jewish self-identification](/Jewish_identity)." In 2020, the demographers [Arnold Dashefsky](/Arnold_Dashefsky) and Ira M. Sheskin, in their meticulous [American Jewish Yearbook](/American_Jewish_Yearbook), estimated the [American Jewish population](/American_Jews) to be 7.15 million, representing 2.17% of the country's then 329.5 million inhabitants. In that same year, another organization, employing its own methodologies, estimated the [American Jewish population](/American_Jews) at 7.6 million people, accounting for 2.4% of the total [US population](/Demographics_of_the_United_States). This latter figure notably included 4.9 million adults who explicitly identified their religion as [Jewish](/Judaism), 1.2 million [Jewish adults](/Jews) who, with typical modern ambivalence, identified with no particular religion, and 1.6 million [Jewish children](/Judaism).

A 2020 study by the ever-observant [Pew Research Center](/Pew_Research_Center) further refined these estimates, placing the core [American Jewish population](/American_Jews) at 7.5 million individuals, encompassing 5.8 million [Jewish adults](/Jews). This study also revealed that the median age of the [American Jewish population](/American_Jews) is 49 years, suggesting a demographic skew towards an older cohort. Approximately 18% of [American Jews](/American_Jews) are under the age of 30, while a substantial 49% are aged 50 and older—a stark reminder of the relentless march of time. The study also found that a modest but significant 9% of [American Jews](/American_Jews) identify as [LGBT](/LGBT).

The [American Jewish Yearbook](/American_Jewish_Yearbook) population survey had previously placed the number of [American Jews](/American_Jews) at 6.4 million, or roughly 2.1% of the total population. This figure was considerably higher than the estimate from the earlier 2000–2001 National Jewish Population estimates, which had pegged the number at 5.2 million [Jews](/Jews). A 2007 study released by the [Steinhardt Social Research Institute](/Steinhardt_Social_Research_Institute) (SSRI) at [Brandeis University](/Brandeis_University) presented compelling evidence suggesting that both these figures might be underestimations, proposing a potential range of 7.0–7.4 million [Americans of Jewish descent](/American_Jews). However, it's crucial to note that these higher estimates were derived by including all non-Jewish family members and household members, rather than solely surveyed individuals, a methodological choice that, predictably, inflates the numbers. A 2019 study by the [Jews of Color Initiative](/Jews_of_Color_Initiative) found that approximately 12-15% of [Jews](/Jews) in the [United States](/United_States)—roughly 1,000,000 out of 7,200,000—identify as multiracial and [Jews of color](/Jews_of_color), a demographic reality that challenges simplistic notions of [Jewish identity](/Jewish_identity).

The overall population of [Americans of Jewish descent](/American_Jews) is, demographically speaking, characterized by an aging composition and rather low fertility rates, falling significantly below the generational replacement threshold. This, of course, signals a slow, steady decline in the absence of other factors. However, the [Orthodox Jewish](/Orthodox_Jewish) population, concentrated primarily in the [Northeastern United States](/Northeastern_United_States), presents a stark contrast, exhibiting fertility rates that are notably higher than both generational replacement levels and the average [U.S. population](/Demographics_of_the_United_States). It seems some communities defy the broader trends with a stubborn adherence to tradition.

The [National Jewish Population Survey](/National_Jewish_Population_Survey) of 1990, in its attempt to categorize the uncategorizable, asked 4.5 million [adult Jews](/Jews) to identify their denomination. The national tally revealed that 38% aligned with the [Reform tradition](/Reform_Judaism), 35% with [Conservative Judaism](/Conservative_Judaism), a smaller 6% with [Orthodox Judaism](/Orthodox_Judaism), and a modest 1% with [Reconstructionists](/Reconstructionist_Judaism). A curious 10% linked themselves to some other, less defined tradition, and another 10% simply declared themselves "just [Jewish](/Jews)." Fast forward to 2013, [Pew Research's Jewish population survey](/Pew_Research_Center) found that 35% of [American Jews](/American_Jews) identified as [Reform](/Reform_Judaism), 18% as [Conservative](/Conservative_Judaism), 10% as [Orthodox](/Orthodox_Judaism), and 6% with other sects, leaving a substantial 30% to simply float without a denominational label. Pew's 2020 poll updated these figures, showing 37% affiliated with [Reform Judaism](/Reform_Judaism), 17% with [Conservative Judaism](/Conservative_Judaism), and 9% with [Orthodox Judaism](/Orthodox_Judaism). Unsurprisingly, younger [Jews](/Jews) are more inclined to identify as [Orthodox](/Orthodox_Judaism) or, with a certain rebellious flair, as entirely unaffiliated, compared to their older, more traditionally aligned counterparts.

Many [Jews](/Jews) are, quite predictably, concentrated in the [Northeastern United States](/Northeastern_United_States), particularly clustered around [New York City](/New_York_City). The world's largest [menorah](/Hanukkah_menorah), a beacon of light in the winter darkness, is annually illuminated at [Grand Army Plaza](/Grand_Army_Plaza,_Manhattan) in [Manhattan](/Manhattan), while [New Jersey](/New_Jersey) boasts its own largest menorah, similarly celebrated in [Monroe Township](/Monroe_Township,_Middlesex_County,_New_Jersey), [Middlesex County](/Middlesex_County,_New_Jersey). Substantial [Jewish populations](/Jewish_population_by_city) also reside in [South Florida](/South_Florida), [Los Angeles](/Los_Angeles), and other major metropolitan areas, such as [Chicago](/Chicago), [San Francisco](/San_Francisco), or [Atlanta](/Atlanta). Indeed, the metropolitan areas of [New York City](/New_York_City), [Los Angeles](/Los_Angeles), and [Miami](/Miami) collectively host nearly a quarter of the world's [Jews](/Jews), with the [New York City metropolitan area](/New_York_metropolitan_area) itself containing approximately a quarter of all [Jews](/Jews) residing in the [United States](/United_States)—a truly staggering concentration of human experience.

