The [New York City metropolitan area](/New_York_metropolitan_area) stands as the second-largest [Jewish population center](/Jewish_population_by_city) in the entire world, surpassed only by the [Tel Aviv metropolitan area](/Tel_Aviv_metropolitan_area) in [Israel](/Israel)—a testament to its enduring significance. Several other major urban centers across the [United States](/United_States) also host substantial [Jewish communities](/Jews), including the sprawling expanse of [Los Angeles](/Los_Angeles), the vibrant cultural mosaic of [Miami](/Miami), the historic charm of [Baltimore](/History_of_the_Jews_in_Baltimore), the intellectual hub of [Boston](/Boston), the midwestern might of [Chicago](/Chicago), the scenic beauty of [San Francisco](/San_Francisco), and the foundational history of [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia). In a predictable pattern of suburban migration, the majority of [Jewish families](/Jews) in many metropolitan areas have, with a certain quiet determination, relocated to suburban enclaves. The [Greater Phoenix](/Greater_Phoenix) area, for instance, was home to approximately 83,000 [Jews](/Jews) in 2002 and has experienced rapid growth since, reflecting broader demographic shifts.

The highest [Jewish population](/Jewish_population_by_city) on a per-capita basis for incorporated areas in the [U.S.](/United_States) are found in distinct pockets. [Kiryas Joel Village, New York](/Kiryas_Joel,_New_York), boasts a staggering figure greater than 93% (based on language spoken in the home), a clear indicator of its [Haredi Jewish](/Haredi_Judaism) concentration. The City of [Beverly Hills, California](/Beverly_Hills,_California), with 61%, reflects a different, often more secular, [Jewish demographic](/Jews). [Lakewood Township, New Jersey](/Lakewood_Township,_New_Jersey), at 59%, also shows a high concentration of [Haredi Jews](/Haredi_Judaism). It is noteworthy that two of these incorporated areas, [Kiryas Joel](/Kiryas_Joel,_New_York) and [Lakewood](/Lakewood_Township,_New_Jersey), are characterized by a high concentration of [Haredi Jews](/Haredi_Judaism), while [Beverly Hills](/Beverly_Hills,_California) represents a high concentration of non-[Orthodox Jews](/Orthodox_Judaism), illustrating the diverse expressions of [Jewish life](/Jewish_culture) even in concentrated areas.

The phenomenon of [Israeli migration](/Yerida) to the [US](/United_States) is often termed [Yerida](/Yerida), a concept that carries its own complex emotional and cultural baggage. The [Israeli immigrant community in America](/Israeli_American) is, comparatively, less geographically widespread. Significant [Israeli immigrant communities](/Israeli_American) in the [United States](/United_States) are primarily found in the [New York City metropolitan area](/New_York_metropolitan_area), [Los Angeles](/Los_Angeles), [Miami](/Miami), and [Chicago](/Chicago).

The [Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development](/Organisation_for_Economic_Co-operation_and_Development) (OECD) calculated an 'expatriate rate' of 2.9 persons per thousand for [Israel](/Israel) in 2005, placing it squarely in the mid-range of expatriate rates among the 175 [OECD](/OECD) countries examined, a statistic that, if one cares to interpret it, suggests a certain human tendency towards global mobility.

According to the 2001 undertaking of the [National Jewish Population Survey](/National_Jewish_Population_Survey), 4.3 million [American Jews](/American_Jews) possess some form of strong, discernible connection to the [Jewish community](/Jews), whether that connection manifests as overtly religious or more subtly cultural.

